<p>The <code>in</code> function tests if a value is in a list of values.</p>

<h2>Basic Usage</h2>
<pre>{open}if {open}echo 'apple' | in('apple', 'banana', 'cherry'){close}{close}Found{open}/if{close}</pre>
{if {echo 'apple' | in('apple', 'banana', 'cherry')}}<p>Result: <b>apple is in the list</b></p>{/if}

<h2>Not Found</h2>
<pre>{open}if not {open}echo 'grape' | in('apple', 'banana', 'cherry'){close}{close}Not in list{open}/if{close}</pre>
{if not {echo 'grape' | in('apple', 'banana', 'cherry')}}<p>Result: <b>grape is NOT in the list</b></p>{/if}

<h2>With Variable</h2>
{set $fruit = 'banana'}
<pre>{open}set $fruit = 'banana'{close}
{open}if {open}echo $fruit | in('apple', 'banana', 'cherry'){close}{close}Valid fruit{open}/if{close}</pre>
{if {echo $fruit | in('apple', 'banana', 'cherry')}}<p>Check: <b>{echo $fruit} is a valid fruit</b></p>{/if}

<h2>Chained Example</h2>
<pre>{open}if {open}echo $filePath | afterLast('.') | lower | in('txt', 'pdf', 'doc'){close}{close}Document{open}/if{close}</pre>
{if {echo $filePath | afterLast('.') | lower | in('txt', 'pdf', 'doc')}}<p>File type: <b>This is a document file</b></p>{/if}

<h2>Note</h2>
<p>Returns 1 (true) or 0 (false). Each value must be quoted separately.</p>
